  "doc_id": "53783",
  "text": "The output of the photodiode sensors were sent to an amplifier and fed into an analog-to-digital converter (Sound Blaster Live, -120 dB noise floor) positioned outside the chamber, and recorded at a sampling rate of 10 kHz. WBF was measured during the first minute of flight after the rest period. Each fly's wing-beat data were saved in a digital file for later processing. An individual fly's WBF was determined as the average of five to ten one-second samples of flight. This sampling scheme has been shown to be sufficiently representative of the average WBF in phototaxic flight [CITATION_1] . For each one-second sample, the wing-beat waveform was FastFourier transformed and the frequency corresponding to the peak of this function was determined as the WBF for that sample (i.e., 1-Hz frequency resolution).",
